04286nam a22006015i 9780292780927DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211979txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927809277 a10.7560/7400682doi  a(DE-B1597)587905  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aHIS0361302bisacsh04a976.4/04/09241 aMcCutchan, Joseph D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMier Expedition Diary :bA Texan Prisoner's Account /cJoseph D. McCutchan; ed. by Joseph Milton Nance. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1979  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tBiographical Sketch of Joseph D. McCutchan -- tIntroductory Chapter -- tChapter of Preface -- tI. Departure for the Rio Grande -- tII. Capture of Loredo by the Texians -- tChapter III The Texians reorganize under Col. Wm. S. Fisher -- tChapter iv The disposition of the men as related to our engagement with the enemy -- tChapter v The disposition of the wounded Texians made by Ampudia -- tV-a. McCutchan's March to Mexico City -- tVI March of the Main Body of Prisoners towards the City of Mexico -- tVII. An Account of the March of Col. Fisher and His Companions -- tChapter VIII On the Way Home -- tChapter IX. List of men comprising the command of Col. Wm. S. Fisher -- tAppendices -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew episodes in Texas history have excited more popular interest than the Mier Expedition of 1842. Nineteen-year-old Joseph D. McCutchan was among the 300 Texans who, without the cover of the Lone Star flag, launched their own disastrous invasion across the Rio Grande. McCutchan's diary provides a vivid account of his experience—the Texans' quick dispatch by Mexican troops at the town of Mier, the hardships of a forced march to Mexico City, over twenty months of imprisonment, and the journey back home after release. Although there are other firsthand accounts of the Mier Expedition, McCutchan was the only diarist who followed the Tampico route to Mexico City. His account documents a different experience than that of the main body of prisoners who marched to the national capital by way of Monterrey, Saltillo, and Agua Nueva. Among the last of the prisoners to be freed, McCutchan covers in his journal the whole period of confinement from December 26, 1842, to the final release on September 16, 1844. The McCutchan diary is set apart from other Mier accounts not only by the new information it provides, but also by Joseph Milton Nance's superb editing. Nance is an acknowledged authority on the hostilities between Texas and Mexico during the era of the Texas Republic. He has transcribed, edited, and annotated the diary with characteristic scholarship and painstaking attention to detail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / Southwest (AZ, NM, OK, TX).2bisacsh1 aKenamore, Jane A.1 aNance, Joseph Milton, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292780927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292780927/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK